ar Years – Afterlives of Comintern Aesthetics -- t12 The Revolutionary Romanticism of Alice Childress’s “Conversations from Life” -- t13 When Comintern and Cominform Aesthetics Meet: Socialist Realism in Eastern Europe, 1956 and Beyond -- t14 Visions of the Future: Soviet Art, Architecture, and Film during and after the Comintern Years -- t15 Comintern Media Experiments, Leftist Exile, and World Literature from East Berlin -- t16 Workers of the World, Unite! -- tCoda -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFounded by Vladimir Lenin in 1919 to instigate a world revolution, the Comintern advanced not just the proletarian struggle but also a wide variety of radical causes, including those against imperialism and racism in settings as varied as Ireland, India, the United States, and China. Notoriously, and from the organization’s outset, these causes grew ever more subservient to Soviet state interest and Stalinist centralization. Comintern Aesthetics shows how the cultural and political networks emerging from the Comintern have continued, even after its demise in 1943. Tracking these networks through a multiplicity of artistic forms geared towards advancing a common, liberated humanity, this volume captures the failure of a Soviet-centered world revolution, but also its enduring allure in the present. The sixteen chapters in this edited volume examine cultural and revolutionary circuits that once connected Moscow to China, Southeast Asia, India, the Near East, Eastern Europe, Germany, Spain, and the Americas. The Soviet Union of the interwar years provided a template for the convergence of party politics and cultural history, but the volume traces how this template was adapted and reworked around the world. By emphasizing the shared, Soviet routes of these far-flung circuits, Comintern Aesthetics recaptures a long-lost moment in which cultures could not only transform perception, but also highlight alternatives to capitalism, namely, an anti-colonial world imaginary foregrounding race, class, and gender equality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAestheticsxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunism and culturexHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunism and literaturexHistoryy20th century. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Eastern (see also Russian & Former Soviet Union).2bisacsh  aAmerican Studies.  aComintern.  aCommunist International.  aLenin.  aMarxism.  aSoviet culture.  aaesthetics.  acritical race studies.  aliterature.  aproletarian struggle.  atranslocal studies.  atransnational literature.1 aBaldwin, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Katerina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDay, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrenko, Evgeny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFibla-Gutiérrez, Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlatley, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlaser, Amelia , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGlaser, Amelia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhrustaleva, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiaer, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawton, Dominick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Steven S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Steven S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPaperny, Vladimir, eco